Throughout her career, Moutoussamy-Ashe-who
was enthralled by Gordon Parks's photobooks as a child
and studied with Garry Winogrand-has worked in the
tradition of street photography, particularly the mode
concerned with making visible people and communities
otherwise largely unseen in the medium." She grew
up on the segregated South Side of Chicago during the
1950s and '60s. Reflecting on her trips to South Africa,
Moutoussamy-Ashe wrote, "My involvement in South
Africa became more emotional as I found some experi-
ences similar to those of Black Americans." Her deeply
personal and empathic images testify to these parallels
as well as the specificities of local conditions, offering
a visual record of apartheid South Africa centered as
much on the experiences of individuals as on the state
in which they lived. -YK

"Origami-collage of inked & colored penciled rice
paper, fumage, watercolor, plastic pigment... latex
paint, lead and colored pencil on silk fibered Indian
handmade paper," read an item on the checklist for
this exhibition, demonstrating the kaleidoscopic array
of materials and techniques the artist combined into
a single work." Banerjee's repertory of mark making
included both traditional and unorthodox approaches.
